Friends,

I decided to ask a question here because I know that http://scuttlebot.io is a bit out of date and it might not be accurate regarding what I want to implement for patchfox at the moment.

I want to add a _join pub_ feature. In that site, it appears that it is as simple as:

~~~~
sbot.invite.accept(code, function (err) {
  // ...
})
~~~~

But checking the Patchwork code in [invite/invite.js](https://github.com/ssbc/patchwork/blob/33bda27b8cca77badcd0c336d1d6bf580c8ff077/lib/depject/invite/invite.js):

~~~~
...
    ssbClient(null, {
      remote: data.invite,
      manifest: { invite: { use: 'async' }, getAddress: 'async' },
      appKey: config.caps && config.caps.shs
    }, function (err, sbot) {
      if (err) return cb(err)
      progress.set('Requesting follow...')

      // ask them to follow us
      sbot.invite.use({ feed: id }, function (err) {
        if (err) {
          // the probably already follow us
          api.contact.async.followerOf(id, data.key, function (_, follows) {
            if (follows) {
              cb()
            } else {
              next()
            }
          })
        } else {
          next()
        }
      })
    })
...
~~~~

It appears it is launching a second `ssb-client`, connecting directly to the pub and issuing muxrpc commands to it. This sounds like it is a common enough feature that I was expecting it to be a simple call (as in someone would've abstracted it already). 

So, can someone here spare some comments on how to join a pub? I don't want to implement this the wrong way.

Thanks a ton for the help, here is a digital 🍇 and a 🍊 for helping me out.

# Help wanted

The code that fetches the messages for the Zines is:

~~~~
const getContentForChannel = c => {
    content = [];
    channel = c;
    let query = [
      {
        $filter: {
          value: {
            content: {
              channel: c,
              type: { $in: ["post", "blog"] }
            }
          }
        }
      }
    ];

    pull(
      sbot.query.read({
        query,
        reverse: true
      }),
      ssb.filterWithUserFilters(),
      pull.filter(msg => {
        if (msg.value.content.type === "post") {
          let root = msg.value.content.root;
          let branch = msg.value.content.branch;

          if (branch) return false;
          if (root && root !== msg.key) return false;
        }
        return true;
      }),
      pull.take(limit),
      pull.drain(function(data) {
        content.push(data);
        content = content;
      })
    );
  };
~~~~

I'm having trouble with sorting. I can see messages from years ago when I am sure there were other _root_ messages between that old msg and the new ones. I'm not sure how to change this to make sure I'm getting the recent ones. I expected that by having `reverse: true` I'd end up with the recent stuff but maybe that is not the case at all.

Regarding the new source, the most interesting file at the moment is [backup.js](https://github.com/ssbc/ssb-backup-tool/blob/master/backup.js) which contains the different phases the backup process goes through. Each phase is a [mithril component](https://mithril.js.org/#components) and the specific backuping code goes into the [oncreate lifecycle method for the component](https://mithril.js.org/lifecycle-methods.html#oncreate). So as components are replaced into view by changing the current route, the backup process moves through its phases.

As an example of a backup phase, lets focus on _phase  3 - connect to SSB server_ which is responsible for connecting to the running ssb-server:

~~~~
const connect = {
    oncreate: function (vnode) {
        ssbClient(config, (err, server) => {
            if (err) {
                console.error("err", err)
                m.route.set("/backup/servernotrunning")
            } else {
                sbot = server
                backup.feed = sbot.id
                m.route.set("/backup/getdatafromserver")
            }
        })
    },
    view: function (vnode) {
        return m(MessageWithIndeterminateProgress, {
            content: `Attempting to connect to the running ssb-server...`
        })
    }
}
~~~~

Depending on if it can connect or not, it will set a script local variable `sbot` and redirect to the next phase/route. I think this code might be interesting for those wanting to contribute to a SSBC project because I am intentionally making it friendly and simple.

There were other minor problems, just small friction stuff. For example, at the moment, each package has a declaration JS and one or more Svelte components which are views. This was done because the `MessageRenderer` needs extra information about a given component to figure out if it can handle a specific message or not. So for example for the `vote` message, it loops all packages checking which one has `package.messageType = "vote"`, then it picks the Svelte view inside `package.view`. If we could add arbitrary data to a Svelte component and check it into runtime, this wouldn't be necessary. You can do some of this by tweaking the options in the Svelte compiler though.

Part of making Patchfox what I want it to be is being able to create reusable, easy to use, high level components to be used by everyone here to build their little apps and packages. So that you could (theoretically) do something like:

~~~~
class BlogFeed extends Feed {
  query() {
    return new SSBQuery({type: "blog"})
  }
}

let allBlogs = new BlogFeed()

render(allBlogs)
~~~~

Where most of the logic used by `BlogFeed` is actually encapsulated in `Feed` so that the user doesn't need to know the internals. This becomes even more important as the concept of Patchfox little apps mature and people start developing their own little apps. There needs to be an easy to use, non-hackish, framework in place to make this as frictionless as possible.

A way that all the problems mentioned above manifests is that lots of Patchfox components reinvent the wheel over and over again. A good example is _liking a message_, every message renderer component (and there is at least one for each message type, except `about` which has two different renderer at the moment depending if it is contact related or gathering related) has functions for liking, unliking and checking if you liked, the given message. Every single one of them has this:

~~~~
 ssb.votes(msg.key).then(ms => {
    ms.forEach(m => {
      let author = m.value.author;
      if (author === ssb.feed && m.value.content.vote.value === 1) {
        liked = true;
      }
    });
  });

  const likeChanged = ev => {
    let v = ev.target.checked;
    if (v) {
      ssb
        .like(msg.key)
        .then(() => console.log("liked", msg.key))
        .catch(() => (liked = false));
    } else {
      ssb
        .unlike(msg.key)
        .then(() => console.log("unliked", msg.key))
        .catch(() => (liked = true));
    }
  };
~~~~

With Svelte, this should be encapsulated into a `Votes` component. Why can't we have a generic message handler that just adds this? The `MessageRenderer` can't automatically add this to a footer because slots don't work well. So each message renderer ended up reimplementing likes because there is no inheritance and composition doesn't play well with nesting components.

