Friends, 

Suppose I have an array of _throughs_ and I want to insert them in the middle of a _pull_, as in:

~~~~
pull(
  sbot.createHistoryStream(),
  myArrayWithThroughs,
  pull.collect(...)
)
~~~~

Anyone know how to do this? 

Oh, you're asking: _"why I have an array of throughs?"_, well the idea is that with the new #patchfox SSB library you can register _through_ pipelines as a user of the library and they will be added to calls that use pull stream. Example:

~~~~

let limit = () => pull.take(10)

let main = async (config) => {

    try {
        ssb.pipelines.thread.use(limit)

        await ssb.connect(config.keys, config.remote)
        let msgs = await ssb.threads.public()
        console.log(msgs)

    } catch (n) {
        console.error(n)
    }
}
~~~~

cc: #ssb-learning #ssb-dev

The cool thing about:

~~~~
import ssb from "../platform/ssb/ssb.js"
import pull from "../web_modules/pull-stream.js"

let limit = () => pull.take(10)

let main = async (config) => {

    try {
        ssb.pipelines.thread.use(limit)

        await ssb.connect(config.keys, config.remote)

        let msgs = await ssb.threads.public()
        console.log(msgs)

    } catch (n) {
        console.error(n)
    }
}
~~~~

Is that it requires no transpilation. This is the exact code the browser is executing. The browser is happy. I am happy.

[@Christian Bundy](@+oaWWDs8g73EZFUMfW37R/ULtFEjwKN/DczvdYihjbU=.ed25519),

I tried with the spread operator first and it didn't work. The problem was not the spread of course. Originally, the array contained functions that when executed returned thinks like `pull.take(2)`, so it caused an error because what needed to be there was not those functions but the result of executing them. I thought the problem was with the spread and converted to `pull.apply`. Of course the problem persisted and then I figured out what happening but since I already had the _apply_ based code there, I used it.

The pipeline code is:

~~~~
let pipelines = {
    threadPipes: new Set(),
    messagePipes: new Set(),
    thread: {
        use: func => pipelines.threadPipes.add(func),
        get: () => [...pipelines.threadPipes].map(p => p.apply(p))
    },
    message: {
        use: func => pipelines.messagePipes.add(func),
        get: () => [...pipelines.messagePipes].map(p => p.apply(p))
    }
}
~~~~

Now it works.

